{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522392","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522392"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:44:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:44:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13824"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13824","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13824"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.08,0.69,0.05,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6441"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105925"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6441","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6441"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13824"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88400"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12721"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12722"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35155"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38844"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42942"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43444"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105925","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105925"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of a rash on his face and hands, and 5kg loss of weight. The rash has spread to his shoulders and is not pruritic.  He works in a factory making kitchen benchtops, and states he has been feeling more fatigued after work.  He has hypertension and takes perindopril daily. On examination, he appears unwell with a pulse rate of 88/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. There is a rash as shown in the image on his face, hands and shoulders.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Methotrexate therapy","Intravenous immunoglobulin","High-dose oral prednisone","Janus kinase inhibitors","Hydroxychloroquine"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with characteristic skin findings heliotrope rash on eyelids of dermatomyositis, as well as the more subtle signs of fatigue and weight loss. Dermatomyositis is associated with proximal muscle weakness that may occur with the rash days to years later. There is some genetic predisposition and also can be triggered by medications, malignancy, viral infections and silica exposure - such as in this scenario of a factory worker with cutting benchtops. The most appropriate initial management for this condition is to \u003Cstrong\u003Einitiate high-dose oral prednisone\u003C/strong\u003E. Systemic corticosteroids are the mainstay of treatment for dermatomyositis and can rapidly improve both muscle strength and skin manifestations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydroxychloroquine\u003C/strong\u003E is often used as a steroid-sparing agent in dermatomyositis, particularly for skin manifestations. However, it is not typically used as first-line therapy, especially in cases with significant muscle involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous immunoglobulin\u003C/strong\u003E can be effective in dermatomyositis, but it is usually reserved for cases that are refractory to first-line treatments or in patients with severe, rapidly progressive disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMethotrexate\u003C/strong\u003E is a steroid-sparing agent that can be used in dermatomyositis, but it is typically introduced after initial treatment with corticosteroids, not as a first-line therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EJanus kinase inhibitors \u003C/strong\u003Eare still under further studies though demonstrate some response with refractory dermatomyositis. Similarly, it is not used for first-line management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that in adult-onset dermatomyositis, especially in patients over 60 and a history of weight loss, there is an increased risk of associated malignancy. Therefore, after initiating treatment, a thorough cancer screening should be performed. This typically includes age-appropriate cancer screenings plus additional tests such as CT chest/abdomen/pelvis, and in some cases, PET scan.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Systemic corticosteroids are the first-line treatment for dermatomyositis.","A heliotrope rash associated with weight loss or muscle weakness should prompt investigation for dermatomyositis."],"references":["Ngan, V. Adult-onet dermatomyositis. In: DermNet [online]. 2020. Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/adult-onset-dermatomyositis","Smith L, Paik J. Promising and Upcoming Treatments in Myositis. In. Current Rheumatology Rep. [online]. 2020:22 (10).  Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7955788/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88400"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13824"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20771"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20771","links":{"self":"h